1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Hi, in this lesson we are going to explore user management.

2
00:00:05,760 --> 00:00:08,760
In WordPress you can assign roles which was designed to give the site owner the ability

3
00:00:10,460 --> 00:00:13,460
to control what users can and cannot do within the site.

4
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:17,800
There are different roles to explore and each role is allowed to perform a set of tasks.

5
00:00:20,200 --> 00:00:23,200
Knowing the differences is important as it will help you keep your site protected and

6
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:27,680
ensure that your editors and contributors are informed about their abilities and the

7
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:31,920
part that they play.

8
00:00:31,640 --> 00:00:34,640
In this video we will explain five roles and their capabilities and explore what the dashboard

9
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:39,560
looks like from the perspective of each role.

10
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:42,800
The five main roles you can assign are the administrator, editor, author, contributor

11
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:51,760
and subscriber.

12
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:52,760
Let's start with the administrator.

13
00:00:53,680 --> 00:00:56,680
Upon installing WordPress an administrator role is automatically created and it is

14
00:00:58,760 --> 00:01:01,760
somebody who has access to all the administration features within a single site.

15
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:06,680
For multi-site owners the super admin has these capabilities.

16
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:11,960
Next we have the editor.

17
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:13,640
The editor is somebody who can publish and manage posts including the posts of other

18
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:18,440
users.

19
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:20,160
An author on the other hand is somebody who can only publish and manage their own posts.

20
00:01:23,480 --> 00:01:26,480
Then we move on to a contributor.

21
00:01:26,280 --> 00:01:29,280
This is somebody who can write and manage their own posts but cannot publish them.

22
00:01:31,240 --> 00:01:34,240
And lastly a subscriber is somebody who can only manage their profile and it is usually

23
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:39,000
made for subscription type websites.

24
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
The administrator is at the top of the WordPress ladder and there is usually only one per website.

25
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:47,880
As mentioned the administrator is somebody who has access to all the administration features

26
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:52,760
within a single site.

27
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:54,920
The administrator can publish, edit and delete posts and pages, edit code, they can manage

28
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:02,480
media, plugins, themes, other accounts and settings.

29
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:07,680
They basically have the keys to all the doors of the site.

30
00:02:08,640 --> 00:02:11,640
The administrator can update their profile top right of their dashboard page or by making

31
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:18,120
their way to Users, clicking on profile and making the necessary updates there.

32
00:02:25,240 --> 00:02:28,240
The administrator also has the power to create and manage other users.

33
00:02:31,320 --> 00:02:34,320
To create a new user click on Add new.

34
00:02:35,040 --> 00:02:38,040
On the Add new user page create a new user by assigning them a username, a valid email

35
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:43,480
address and any other optional details.

36
00:02:44,280 --> 00:02:47,280
In the next section choose an appropriate role for this user.

37
00:02:48,160 --> 00:02:51,160
And when you are ready click Add new user.

38
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:54,320
A new user will automatically be sent a welcome email by WordPress with their new logging

39
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:58,800
information including the generated password.

40
00:02:58,960 --> 00:03:01,960
The user will be prompted to login and to change their password to one of their liking.

41
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:06,960
To change the role of an existing user you can select Edit, open the role drop down and

42
00:03:10,360 --> 00:03:13,360
select a different role or no role for the site at all.

43
00:03:14,880 --> 00:03:17,880
If you would like to change the role of multiple users you can use the check boxes to the left

44
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:22,600
of the user to make the changes simultaneously.

45
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:27,520
If you delete a user you have the option to delete all the content they have created or

46
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
to reassign it to a different user.

47
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:39,200
And once you have made your choice click on Confirm deletion.

48
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:43,480
To customize the view of the users table click on Screen options top right.

49
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:48,120
Yeah you can specify which columns you would like to view and the number of users you want

50
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:53,200
to view per page.

51
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:54,800
And once you are done click apply.

52
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:58,040
Editors have high level of access as they usually manage content.

53
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:02,600
Let's see what the dashboard looks like for an editor.

54
00:04:02,960 --> 00:04:05,960
An editor is someone who can create, edit, publish and delete posts and pages including

55
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:11,720
the posts of other users.

56
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
They are also capable of managing media and comments.

57
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:17,600
So what can't they do?

58
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Editors cannot install themes, plugins or approve any updates.

59
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:24,560
They also don't have access to any site settings.

60
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:27,400
Their role is to manage the work of other users and contributors.

61
00:04:28,760 --> 00:04:31,760
The role of an author is in the name, their role is to provide content to the site and

62
00:04:33,280 --> 00:04:36,280
nothing else.

63
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:37,600
They are therefore only able to publish and manage their own posts and not those of others.

64
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:43,200
As you will notice they can upload media and create, edit, publish and delete their own

65
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:49,560
posts.

66
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:50,760
Authors are therefore only in charge of adding content to a site and don't have any administrative

67
00:04:52,800 --> 00:04:55,800
rights.

68
00:04:54,840 --> 00:04:57,840
Let's say you have somebody who is willing to contribute content to your site as a once

69
00:04:58,720 --> 00:05:01,720
off.

70
00:05:00,080 --> 00:05:03,080
While in the role of contributor is perfect for that individual.

71
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:06,840
Seeing that they are not one of the authors, they will only be able to write and manage

72
00:05:07,520 --> 00:05:10,520
their posts but cannot publish them.

73
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:13,200
A contributor cannot upload media files and when they publish content, it will first be

74
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:18,760
reviewed before publishing.

75
00:05:18,280 --> 00:05:21,280
As you will notice it is almost the same as being an author but with a few more limitations.

76
00:05:23,880 --> 00:05:26,880
The last role we will be looking at is the subscriber.

77
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:30,720
Subscribers only have access to managing their own profiles and nothing else.

78
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:35,200
If we are into the dashboard of a subscriber, we will see they can only read all the posts

79
00:05:37,500 --> 00:05:40,500
on the site and change their profiles.

80
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:43,560
This is not a role that will be used on many sites, mostly subscription based websites.

81
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:49,640
And finally you may also decide to search and install a user role plugin to extend this

82
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:54,960
feature's functionality.

83
00:05:54,280 --> 00:05:57,280
All the best managing the various user roles you wish to assign.

